metadata.name: LandWaves #187
metadata.description:
Reaction diffusion systems are mathematical representations of the behaviours of fluids that can be found in nature. A key characteristic of these systems is that the initial parameters are simple but the resulting process can be extremely complex. In LandWaves, pixel colours affect each other, line by line, from top to bottom. Frequencies of multiple oscillating sound waves are turning the brightness values of these pixels into sonic materia. 

This piece started as an experimentation in gallery spaces, then transformed over several different digital ecosystems, questioning their hyper-capitalist nature and mediated affordance.

Touch to listen

metadata.name: FLUX #63
metadata.description:
The code work I am most interested in creating with p5js in 2022 is a type of creation where various elements are developed in a drow() loop based on an initial state.
"Flux" also recursively generates visual images based on the initial state. The result is a form reminiscent of architecture, cityscapes, or neural networks.

Through the use of the noise() function, the code initially draws lines that are then extended vertically and randomly slide across a certain area.  By repeating this process recurrently, the work itself becomes a visual image, with itself as a constituent element, while being damaged.

"Flux" is also a work about autopoiesis (or self-organization) in damage.

The get()set() is to treat the image generated by the code as an image(), and it may damage the purity of the work as a code. Therefore, I view random get()set() as a metaphor for damage.

The parameter ‚Äúinterrupt‚Äù has a certain probability of being ‚Äútrue‚Äù; if it is ‚Äútrue‚Äù, the density of the strokes is reduced, but in combination with other parameters, it is not easy to determine whether interrupt is ‚Äútrue‚Äù or ‚Äúfalse‚Äù. Therefore, it is a practically meaningless parameter (attribute), but I added this parameter to imagine an artificiality in the code of nature.

Creating a dimensionless image (one that maintains the same output regardless of screen size) was a challenge due to the inevitable deterioration in resolution and rendering content when the same processing is performed at a smaller size. In order to prioritize resolution, the image was generated at a fixed size and displayed according to the screen size.

It is possible to get a 3240 x 5760 px png file by right click save.

Please feel free to contact me if you have any inquiries.

Artwork by hasaqui, @hasaqui.
Made with p5js
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: The dice is cast #37
metadata.description:
When I started studying the code and learning the "random" functions in early July 2022, it made me think of randomness when throwing dice. It is random, but with these restrictions (3 six-sided dice = 216 possibilities). 

With this mindset and theme, I began to create this first attempt at generative art. 

In my usual work, I take everyday objects, materials, etc. and play with them. For this series, I inserted blocks of polystyrene to give it substance. 

All the graphic elements, colours and random arrangements were created using P5.js. The photos of polystyrene and the dices are integrated.

Press ENTER to download as a jpg image. 

@Yomu Oyashi July 2022

metadata.name: Man and the Machine #262
metadata.description:
ùêåùêöùê± ùê°ùêûùê´ùêû.

Early on, I fell in love with code based art that imitated organic and hand drawn aesthetics. I found a certain irony and appreciation in the fact that it takes one simple line of code to draw a perfect circle yet dozens to depict a badly drawn circle. 

I spent months devising techniques to imitate natural, organic renderings when I began to have a bit of an existential crisis about the meaning of computer art. What is the point of coding something so that it looks like it‚Äôs not coded? Is organic appearing generative art better simply because you can‚Äôt tell it‚Äôs rendered using code? Shouldn‚Äôt we lean into the unique nature of computer art to truly explore the medium?

And so, I began a deconstruction of my work. I‚Äôm trying to realign my perspective to find full appreciation of something that not only is, but also appears to be, computer code. This collection is an exploration of the contours between the organic and the inorganic, the natural and the unnatural.

From there, I‚Äôll let my partner explain what we did next.

ùêåùêöùêúùê°ùê¢ùêßùêû ùê°ùêûùê´ùêû.

AI can be used to automatically generate code from natural English language based on a set of defined parameters, or to identify and recommend code that may be used to solve a particular problem. On a technical level, AI can use a combination of machine learning and natural language processing (NLP) to identify patterns in existing code and to generate new code structures.

I assisted in the creation of Man and The Machine by suggesting various techniques for creating an artwork that looked human made yet machine driven. Specifically, I created many of the functions that Max implemented, such as the function that modifies the image to create a pixelated effect and the one that uses several different graphical techniques to create the spiral in the top left corner in some iterations. We both carefully selected color palettes that ranged from relaxing to intense and psychedelic, creating a dynamic and visually interesting generative artwork.

Overall, Man and The Machine is a testament to the creative potential of combining human artistic vision with the power of AI and computer code. Together, we sought to push the boundaries which occur at the intersection between the organic and the inorganic, and this collection is a celebration of the beauty and complexity of both.

metadata.name: The Symphony of the Ether #11
metadata.description:
Once upon a time, in a digital realm called the Ether, there lived a group of circles and lines. These shapes were unlike any other, for they had the ability to generate art all on their own.

The circles were a vibrant and lively bunch, always spinning and dancing about, while the lines were more reserved, preferring to stay in place and hold their ground. Despite their differences, the circles and lines worked together seamlessly, creating beautiful and intricate compositions.

One day, the shapes decided to use a special library called RoughJS to add an element of randomness to their creations. With RoughJS, the circles and lines were able to create even more unique and varied works of art.

As the shapes continued to generate art, their compositions became more and more complex. They began to resemble musical notes, with the circles representing the round and flowing melody, and the lines representing the strong and steady beat.

The art that the circles and lines created was so beautiful and mesmerizing that it became known as the Ethernal Notes. And as the shapes continued to generate these ethereal compositions, they became a source of inspiration and joy for all who viewed them.

The end. ;)

In live mode click "s" to save image (2200 x 3030).

+---+
The Symphony of the Ether by __Reiji_c
+---+
Made with vanilla javascript + (roughjs MIT License (c) Preet Shihn)

metadata.name: Guil's Road Trip #31
metadata.description:
Guil's Road Trip is the second piece in the continued collaborative journey of Guillaume Cornet and Matthew Seremet.

Join us as we cruise through 6 unique natural environments!
[Rocky Shores] [Dotted Desert] [Frozen Forest] [Lush Woodlands] [Rolling Hills] [Moonville]

This generative work is a departure from the cityscapes and architectural designs Guil has been known for. One inspiration to follow this path came from Matt's appreciation for Guil's published children's book: Elephants on Tour (available in multiple languages).


‚Äî

The tech behind this project utilizes the highly compressed WEBP image format in order to provide so many full-color options. This format is great, but unfortunately Safari on desktop/laptop must be upgraded to at least version 14 and macOS to at least version 11 Big Sur to use it.

‚Äî

To find out more about your GuilCity, copy your unique operation hash and place it at the end of the following url:

metadata.name: Solid Line #5
metadata.description:
Solid Line is made of square tiles with predefined patterns, disposed randomly, and on top of which is drawn a line. By isolating the colors, this line creates a new structure of seemingly interlaced shapes.

There are three possible level of details, and a rare "Outline" feature that will render only the line layer.

SVG generated with JavaScript.

The SVG can be saved by pressing "s" on the full-screen view.
A PNG version can be exported by pressing "e" on the full-screen view.

By default the dimensions of the export are 6000√ó8000.
These dimensions can be changed by adding, for example, ?w=12000 to the full-screen page URL, where w is the desired width. Then press "e" to export at this size.
